oversized clothing that is stretched and can no longer be stretched. No growth. As Stacey or Maureen of Redress noted, the designers and models on The Fashion Show and Mullet Monday are so lithe. Even size 4 models can seem bloated. The extreme diet and overexercise of those models could void any moody-ness.

But smaller size-queens satisfy me when they are confident in their bodies, like top blogger Stephania a.k.a. Miss Moss (a fellow South African Brady girl and all around Bad Ass!), Laura V in Bazel, Connecticut, and Minnesota blogger Sarah of Scantily Clad, who recently tamed the thrift of Olivia.”

Carter Bahrs, a film undergraduate student at The New School in New York City, snapped this shot at a modeling agency that is in his neighborhood where he walked by and was accepted. “I started the piece with a still from when I was first approached by the model scout. At first I didn’t know how to interpret the photo and then I realized it represented the life that young actors, models, directors, and photographers move between in the city: dream glamour and performing reality. Do you then exist in your film self, or do you become your dream self by just wishing it into existence. The last thing that the picture reminded me is that you have to live the dream and embrace you reality. So I committed in my camera.”

I loved photographer Carter Bahrs’ unposed clips of casting directors
